WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.700
 Okay, so now we're going to actually play with a little bit of structured query language, SQL.

00:00:04.700 --> 00:00:12.060
 Now, you can grab, at this URL, you can grab the instructions that I'm using so you can cut and paste it in.

00:00:12.060 --> 00:00:16.520
 Now, the key thing that you've got to do is you've got to find your way to a shell.

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:21.700
 If you're using something like Python Anywhere, you go ahead and open a command line.

00:00:21.700 --> 00:00:25.200
 Now, if we're using Python Anywhere, most of what we're doing is running Django applications,

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:33.000
 but you can really just use Python Anywhere as a, use Python Anywhere as a Unix platform.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.300
 And so, get to a dollar sign prompt, these commands can run on a Mac, they can,

00:00:37.300 --> 00:00:42.120
 I don't know if you can get them working on Windows, but any Linux system, but you can also run it on Python Anywhere.

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:46.100
 So, there's a command to Linux called sqlite3, and then you give it a file name.

00:00:46.100 --> 00:00:51.160
 So, sqlite, as I mentioned, is a very simple database because it does all of its work in one file.

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:55.760
 It's not a, it's not a slouch as a database in terms of its performance and scalability.

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:00.260
 What it's not good at is handling hundreds of people hitting it at the same time

00:01:00.260 --> 00:01:06.760
 and having the database software resolve all those simultaneous accesses.

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:13.000
 But if you type sqlite, you end up in a command line where you get this prompt, sqlite, you know, arrow,

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:20.460
 and there's commands you can type, like .tables says, hey, in this database, which is in this case zip.sqlite3,

00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:24.560
 in this database, what tables exist, and it says there are no tables.

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:26.360
 And then you create some tables.

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:31.560
 Now, this is our first SQL statement, and so you'll learn something about SQL

00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:36.700
 as it looks a little different than other programming languages, and so you say create table.

00:01:36.700 --> 00:01:37.900
 That's one statement.

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:40.920
 You can create things other than tables, and then you have a table name.

00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:46.100
 So, and then you have some parentheses, right, and then you have a series of statements

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:48.900
 about the table that you're working with.

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:53.520
 And so there's just this little language, and there's a name of a column.

00:01:53.520 --> 00:01:57.860
 So these are three columns that we're putting in, id, name, and email.

00:01:57.860 --> 00:01:59.960
 And we have a type.

00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:01.100
 This is an integer.

00:02:01.100 --> 00:02:04.260
 Varchar means variable length string field.

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:06.160
 Not null means it's required.

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:08.960
 Primary key means that it's an auto increment,

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:10.660
 meaning it's going to be supplied by the database.

00:02:10.660 --> 00:02:13.820
 It gives us like a handle for every row.

00:02:13.820 --> 00:02:17.920
 And then Varchar 128 says it's up to 128 characters.

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:23.460
 Now, a key to this is that we're making sort of a contract here.

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:29.500
 And so when we say you gotta do this with 128 characters, you can't put 129 in.

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:35.100
 You can put up to 128, and if you put 129, your database query blows up.

00:02:35.100 --> 00:02:38.020
 And you're like, oh, that's not very nice.

00:02:38.020 --> 00:02:40.420
 And the answer is, well, you told it 128, so

00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:43.060
 it could optimize how it's going to store the data on disk.

00:02:43.060 --> 00:02:49.160
 If you've made this 1,000, it might store it in a different way than if you store 128.

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:52.700
 And so the key is you can make any contract you want, but

00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:54.460
 you gotta live by the contract that you make.

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:56.300
 And so it's not the database hates you.

00:02:56.300 --> 00:02:58.700
 It's you said I'm gonna do 128, and when you do 29,

00:02:58.700 --> 00:03:00.900
 it says you're violating our contract.

00:03:00.900 --> 00:03:02.740
 And so it's up to you.

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:07.700
 So this whole create table ending in a semicolon, that is a single SQL statement.

00:03:07.700 --> 00:03:09.420
 And so we can type it in.

00:03:09.420 --> 00:03:10.860
 We can type it in multiple lines, and

00:03:10.860 --> 00:03:14.460
 you can kinda see how SQLite's using this dot, dot, dot thing to tell you that it's

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:15.860
 in a continuation.

00:03:15.860 --> 00:03:19.100
 And then finally you finish it all and you put a semicolon at the end, and

00:03:19.100 --> 00:03:20.460
 then it does it.

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:24.420
 And then we can ask using dot tables, we can say, is there a table?

00:03:24.420 --> 00:03:26.820
 And yes, it says, yes, it's users.

00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:30.420
 And then there's a command, an SQLite command called dot schema.

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:32.900
 And that says, tell me the schema of users.

00:03:32.900 --> 00:03:36.700
 Now that's in case you hadn't just typed in the create statement.

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:38.780
 It tells you what create statement it would be.

00:03:38.780 --> 00:03:43.180
 And so part of what the database stores in this file SQLite

00:03:43.180 --> 00:03:46.980
 is not only the data for this table called users that you just created, but

00:03:46.980 --> 00:03:48.060
 it also stores the schema.

00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:50.980
 And so you can say, hey, what schema is it?

00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:54.940
 So if I sent you one of these files, like you might upload to my autograder,

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:59.340
 for example, I can inquire into that file using SQLite, and I say, what schema?

00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:00.580
 What tables are here?

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:01.900
 And then I can start looking at the tables.

00:04:01.900 --> 00:04:06.060
 As a matter of fact, that's how I grade these assignments inside of the computer.

00:04:08.300 --> 00:04:10.340
 And so this is just sort of going through some.

00:04:10.340 --> 00:04:11.860
 There's a lot of SQL, but

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:14.700
 the basics is actually surprisingly easy to understand.

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:20.120
 And so insert into, one of the things that SQL does,

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:23.220
 is it tends to use more than one word.

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:28.340
 And it wants to be something, I've met people who have used SQL in their jobs.

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:32.980
 And they just type it, and they don't realize how amazing what they're doing is.

00:04:32.980 --> 00:04:38.540
 They're like, well, just insert, or I delete some stuff, or I select it to read it.

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:42.820
 So it was designed to be easy, cuz if we go back to the basics of SQL,

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:45.340
 it was like, look, there's a lot of complexity down there.

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:48.860
 We wanna hide that complexity, we wanna hand something easy to users.

00:04:48.860 --> 00:04:53.300
 And I write a lot of very complex SQL, and it's a very sophisticated skill.

00:04:53.300 --> 00:04:57.700
 But simple SQL is something I think literally everybody should know how to do.

00:04:57.700 --> 00:05:00.060
 So insert into, then you have a table name, and

00:05:00.060 --> 00:05:02.760
 then you have a parenthesis list of the columns.

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:05.460
 Now, these are the columns that you named in your create statement.

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:07.140
 And then values is a keyword.

00:05:07.140 --> 00:05:09.740
 And then there's a one to one correspondence between

00:05:09.740 --> 00:05:11.540
 the values that you're gonna put in the columns.

00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:14.340
 And these happen to be strings, so we have little quotes around them.

00:05:14.340 --> 00:05:17.420
 They could be integers, they could be dates, they could be all kinds of things,

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:19.260
 floating point numbers, etc.

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:20.940
 And then this has to meet the schema.

00:05:20.940 --> 00:05:25.420
 You can't go putting a number into a string field or a string into a number field.

00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:29.340
 And again, so that would blow up if you can make all kinds of errors.

00:05:29.340 --> 00:05:32.580
 You can either have syntax errors like you forget the word into or something, or

00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:35.980
 you can have errors that are bad, that your data is bad, right?

00:05:35.980 --> 00:05:41.540
 So that's the insert statement, and that adds a row to the end of a table.

00:05:41.540 --> 00:05:47.860
 The delete statement says delete from, and then a table name, and then a where clause.

00:05:47.860 --> 00:05:49.940
 We're gonna see where clause is a lot in SQL.

00:05:49.940 --> 00:05:56.140
 And the key thing is that every, I sort of mentioned in the very beginning that

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:57.900
 there's kind of no loops in SQL.

00:05:57.900 --> 00:06:00.460
 And that's one of the reasons that we sort of love SQL,

00:06:00.460 --> 00:06:02.300
 is you don't have to write loops.

00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:05.920
 And that's because there's kind of an implied loop at the beginning of

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:06.540
 these commands.

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:16.340
 So when you say delete from users, that means delete all rows from users, right?

00:06:16.340 --> 00:06:20.180
 Delete all rows, delete everything from users.

00:06:20.180 --> 00:06:23.540
 So if you don't put this where clause on, if you don't put that where clause on,

00:06:23.540 --> 00:06:25.740
 it actually deletes everything in there.

00:06:25.740 --> 00:06:28.140
 Cuz it's like delete all the rows from users.

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:32.300
 That's the way you can kinda phrase it that way, delete all rows from users.

00:06:32.300 --> 00:06:34.620
 Now the all rows part isn't really there.

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:39.460
 But that just means that it's really important to have a where clause so

00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:41.780
 that you're not actually deleting all the rows.

00:06:41.780 --> 00:06:45.940
 It's saying delete all the rows from users where the email is equal to

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:46.860
 ted@umich.edu.

00:06:46.860 --> 00:06:52.620
 And so what that is, is there's an implied loop of all rows on this delete statement.

00:06:52.620 --> 00:06:55.540
 And the where clause reduces that down to actually one or

00:06:55.540 --> 00:07:00.220
 a couple of rows depending on those rows where this is like an if statement.

00:07:00.220 --> 00:07:03.980
 So this whole thing is like a loop with an if inside of it.

00:07:03.980 --> 00:07:05.540
 That's how it works.

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:08.420
 And this is why a lot of people like it is cuz you don't have to write loops.

00:07:08.420 --> 00:07:12.340
 Because these things sort of like are loops, they have loops built in.

00:07:12.340 --> 00:07:17.180
 So, but this would delete one or a couple of rows depending on whether we had more

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:21.820
 than one row in this where the email was ted@umich.edu.

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:24.900
 Update is really kinda cool.

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:26.180
 You can really zero in.

00:07:26.180 --> 00:07:28.540
 You can zero in to rows and columns.

00:07:28.540 --> 00:07:32.180
 And again, update users, which is the name of the table.

00:07:32.180 --> 00:07:38.140
 Set is, and then name equals, which is the field name and new value.

00:07:38.140 --> 00:07:41.060
 And so you can get any, you can do all the columns.

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:42.200
 You can do one of the columns.

00:07:42.200 --> 00:07:44.180
 You can really zone in on this.

00:07:44.180 --> 00:07:45.180
 And then there's a where clause.

00:07:45.180 --> 00:07:47.460
 Because if you don't put a where clause on the update,

00:07:47.460 --> 00:07:51.260
 it implies that this is for all rows.

00:07:51.260 --> 00:07:53.780
 And you don't really wanna set the name to be Charles for all the rows.

00:07:53.780 --> 00:07:55.660
 You just wanna set the name to be Charles.

00:07:55.660 --> 00:07:56.780
 Where this is true.

00:07:56.780 --> 00:08:02.220
 Because again, this, you could think of this as like update all rows.

00:08:02.220 --> 00:08:07.220
 All rows in users set where.

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:11.140
 And so you just always gotta be thinking that there, it's in.

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:15.100
 So then, so the reading is done with select.

00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:18.900
 I wish that it would be create, read, update, delete.

00:08:18.900 --> 00:08:23.180
 The create is insert, read is select, update is update, and delete is delete.

00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:25.280
 Select is the way that we read stuff out.

00:08:25.280 --> 00:08:29.260
 And so select basically takes a list of columns.

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:32.580
 Like select name, comma, email, or select star.

00:08:32.580 --> 00:08:34.300
 And from, and then a table name.

00:08:34.300 --> 00:08:39.740
 So this select star from users is quite the, almost always the first thing you type.

00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:43.060
 Select star from user, select star from book, select star from whatever.

00:08:43.060 --> 00:08:46.500
 You can also put a where clause on a select.

00:08:46.500 --> 00:08:51.100
 Because this again has this implied all rows kind of a thing going on.

00:08:51.100 --> 00:08:55.780
 And so select all rows from users where email equals c7 human study.

00:08:55.780 --> 00:08:59.940
 And that, that reads much better when you kind of add that all rows logic to it.

00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:05.740
 Databases are good by, with, good at searching.

00:09:05.740 --> 00:09:10.180
 We can do things like add indexes to the databases that make searching and

00:09:10.180 --> 00:09:11.660
 ordering even better.

00:09:11.660 --> 00:09:14.820
 So we might say that email, please, while you're maintaining this data,

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:16.700
 in addition to maintaining the data,

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:19.580
 maintain an index that has a sense of the order of these records.

00:09:19.580 --> 00:09:23.700
 So if I want to sort them ascending or descending, then I can get that, and

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:26.180
 I can get that to be efficient.

00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:30.340
 And so the, you know, order by is just a thing you throw on the end.

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:32.380
 You can add a where clause here as well, and

00:09:32.380 --> 00:09:35.100
 you can have ascending and descending sorts, and it worked great.

00:09:35.100 --> 00:09:42.540
 So this is sort of the first 60% of any SQL is the basic

00:09:42.540 --> 00:09:45.260
 insert, delete, update, and read.

00:09:45.260 --> 00:09:46.740
 And so that is not hard.

00:09:47.980 --> 00:09:52.500
 And the beauty is, is this essence of SQL, the middle part of SQL,

00:09:52.500 --> 00:09:55.900
 is portable across all the databases that I just described.

00:09:55.900 --> 00:09:58.980
 Because every one of those databases that's a modern database,

00:09:58.980 --> 00:10:02.540
 was invented after the invention of SQL.

00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:04.500
 And so life is pretty good.

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:08.380
 Now, there are differences, because when they first built SQL in like,

00:10:08.380 --> 00:10:12.740
 I think '87, I don't know, forgot that time.

00:10:12.740 --> 00:10:17.820
 But when they first built it, they did not realize how powerful they were going to be.

00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:21.380
 And so they, there's a bunch of features that got added by the vendors that were

00:10:21.380 --> 00:10:25.260
 extensions, and some of them are sort of standardized.

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:26.900
 There's another round of standardization, but

00:10:26.900 --> 00:10:29.200
 then there's a whole bunch of features that are a little different.

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:33.460
 But they have, because of competition, they have conceptually the same ideas.

00:10:33.460 --> 00:10:37.180
 Like, there's like a limit clause that limits the number of rows, or

00:10:37.180 --> 00:10:39.060
 starts after a certain number of rows.

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:41.380
 And it's a little different from one database to the other.

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:43.180
 So, but this is just a summary.

00:10:43.180 --> 00:10:44.020
 You should know this.

00:10:44.020 --> 00:10:46.540
 You should just know this forever and ever and ever.

00:10:46.540 --> 00:10:48.620
 And then as you run into a different database,

00:10:48.620 --> 00:10:51.100
 then you'll learn different features for that.

00:10:51.100 --> 00:10:55.940
 A tool that you might want to install on your laptop, if you want to start playing

00:10:55.940 --> 00:11:00.660
 with these SQLite files and not just using the command line, is called SQLite browser.

00:11:00.660 --> 00:11:01.580
 You can download it.

00:11:01.580 --> 00:11:03.500
 It runs on lots of different systems.

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:06.180
 You can then open these .sqlite3 files.

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:11.020
 And you can do stuff to it, including execute the SQL commands right in there.

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:14.460
 And so, a lot of people find this a more interesting and

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:17.100
 easy way to interact with these files.

00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:23.220
 And so, that kind of sums up our really quick introduction to single table SQL.

00:11:23.220 --> 00:11:27.260
 Up next, we'll talk a little bit about multiple table SQL and relationships.

00:11:27.260 --> 00:11:31.580
 And then we'll also talk about how we connect this all to Django

00:11:31.580 --> 00:11:33.100
 through an object relational mapper.

00:11:33.100 --> 00:11:34.100
 So, see you soon.

00:11:34.100 --> 00:11:44.100
 [MUSIC]

